00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:22.390
hard to talk about.
It is the problem here that it involves genitals

00:10:22.390 --> 00:10:25.870
and so it's something
that it's very hard to have a serious conversation

00:10:25.870 --> 00:10:26.870
about.

00:10:26.870 --> 00:10:29.390
KATHY CALVIN: You know, I actually think it's
not a hard subject to

00:10:29.390 --> 00:10:31.770
have a conversation about -- and that Julia
said the right thing.

00:10:31.770 --> 00:10:34.730
I don't think people really understand that
it's still exists.

00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:38.610
It sort of one of those things that we heard
about in our childhood and

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:42.210
we don't hear enough about it today.
So my -- my hat is off to Julia for bringing

00:10:42.210 --> 00:10:44.460
this back up front and
center.

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:47.420
I think the other reason we don't hear as
much about it is it's about

00:10:47.420 --> 00:10:50.080
girls.
And we don't really have an understanding

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:54.830
of the life of 600 million
girls around the world, that they don't get

00:10:54.830 --> 00:10:56.760
to stay in school, they get
married off early.

00:10:56.760 --> 00:11:02.030
They are subject to genital mutilation.
Their lives are challenges in ways that American

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:05.040
girls don't really
understand and when they hear about it, they're

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:08.320
shocked.
They think it's unfair, and they want to do

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:11.520
something.
So yes, there's probably something about how

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:15.300
do we talk about this?
I frankly think reproductive health is just

00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:19.040
as difficult to talk about
especially when it comes to girls, but increasingly

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:21.710
people -- I heard
Melinda Gates yesterday speaking out about

00:11:21.710 --> 00:11:24.800
it.
It's time to deal with these issues and so

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:26.150
here we are.

00:11:26.150 --> 00:11:30.970
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Larry, one of the -- I had
a conversation once with

00:11:30.970 --> 00:11:35.810
a Sudanese diya, a women who does the cutting
and I pushed her on

00:11:35.810 --> 00:11:39.190
genital cutting and she said, this is our
culture.

00:11:39.190 --> 00:11:43.560
This is our religion.
What business is it of you Americans whether

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:44.650
we circumcise our
daughters?

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:47.440
How do we answer her?

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:52.950
LARRY COX: Well, it's a very important question.
And when Amnesty started working on this several

00:11:52.950 --> 00:11:56.620
decades ago, it was a
question that actually for awhile even divided

00:11:56.620 --> 00:11:58.870
our own membership.
People were very afraid that they were being

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:03.140
culturally insensitive or
even imperialistic in taking this on.

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:07.420
I think what makes the difference is hearing
the voices of the actual

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:10.370
women who experienced this and who are fighting
against it.

00:12:10.370 --> 00:12:14.250
It then becomes clear it's not a question
 -- who defines the culture

00:12:14.250 --> 00:12:17.940
and how does culture change?
Culture is not something stagnant.

00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:23.120
Of course, it's easy for us to say, you know,
human rights always trump

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:25.820
culture.
It's also interesting that these cultural

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:30.500
arguments are usually not
always used to justify cruelty and pain that

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:33.821
effect women and not men.
I think if men were being cut in this way,

00:12:33.821 --> 00:12:37.020
somehow the cultural
arguments would fade away.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:42.890
But I think it is very important to: (A) listen
to the women

00:12:42.890 --> 00:12:45.700
themselves make their voices heard because
that completely undercuts

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:49.260
the argument that this is something being
imposed from abroad.

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:53.340
It's not.
And secondly, I think it is important to take

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:56.640
the cultural argument
seriously in the sense that to end the practice,

00:12:56.640 --> 00:13:01.070
one has to really
seriously address how you get the whole community

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:04.560
to understand that
this is something which is not in the interests

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:08.620
of a community, not in
the interests of the girl they care about.

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:13.810
And to take the lead in fact in trying to
stop it.

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:19.500
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Let me, Ann, let me sort
of follow up on that in the

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:24.310
sense that this is something that the West
has pushed hard against

00:13:24.310 --> 00:13:30.700
really since the 1920s.
I think because of British influence Sudan

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:36.580
banned infibulation which is
the worst kind of FGM back in 1925 and a similar

00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:42.010
period in Kenya.
And in fact, it really led in those, especially

00:13:42.010 --> 00:13:45.540
in those early periods,
to something of a backlash.

00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:49.720
It was this sense these outside imperialists
telling us what to do,

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:52.510
this is our culture.
So Ann, if you could maybe talk a little bit

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:57.330
about I mean is it fair to
say that especially since the 1970s when there

00:13:57.330 --> 00:14:03.610
was a ramped up effort
that that effort really didn't, that it really

00:14:03.610 --> 00:14:06.870
was something of a
failure, which is my view.

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:10.722
But that now, in the last ten years or so,
we're kind of getting the

00:14:10.722 --> 00:14:11.722
formula for what works?

00:14:11.722 --> 00:14:18.090
ANN VENEMAN: I think, um, part of the problem
is as you say that

00:14:18.090 --> 00:14:25.570
people react to having them, having them their
cultures, you know, said

00:14:25.570 --> 00:14:31.550
that they're not right.
So as Nick mentioned one of the organizations

00:14:31.550 --> 00:14:35.260
that has been very
successful is an organization called Tostan,

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:40.290
T-O-S-T-A-N, for of you
who want to look it up on the web.

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:44.480
It works primarily in West Africa, but also
across the band of Africa

00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:50.250
where this practice is most prevalent.
But I think the important thing about is that

00:14:50.250 --> 00:14:55.100
it starts at the
community level with community discussions.

00:14:55.100 --> 00:15:00.320
One of the first things that they did was
they no longer referred to it

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:04.530
as female genital mutilation, because the
word "mutilation" is

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:12.260
judgmental, the word cutting is factual.
This came about with conversations with the

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:14.560
leadership of the
communities themselves.

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:19.310
I've visited the first community that Tostan
began in.

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:24.670
And they started by talking with the imam,
the senior leader.

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:29.460
This was a community where men and women were
so separated that the

00:15:29.460 --> 00:15:34.350
women literally had to walk in a different
part of the whole community

00:15:34.350 --> 00:15:39.860
if the men were sitting in the town square.
There was absolutely no mixing of men and

00:15:39.860 --> 00:15:42.200
women.
So they began with the imam to talk about

00:15:42.200 --> 00:15:47.550
the health impacts.
And suddenly the lights go on, and say, well,

00:15:47.550 --> 00:15:51.500
yes, I remember my niece
went a little crazy after this because of

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:56.510
infection.
Well, they had never put the health impacts

00:15:56.510 --> 00:16:00.980
really on the agenda.
So then they begin to talk about it as a human

00:16:00.980 --> 00:16:07.320
rights issue.
The community now, has come together men and

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:14.910
women, not only has this
practice -- they've abandoned it as a community,

00:16:14.910 --> 00:16:19.160
but they've also seen
that the education rates have gone up; the

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:25.050
access to health care has
gone up; better access for women to reproductive

00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:26.800
health services and
attended births.

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:31.090
So there's been a lot of impacts of working
together as a community.

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:35.230
Now the other thing that they found, again,
a cultural aspect is you

00:16:35.230 --> 00:16:39.810
couldn't just do it in one community.
And so you had to reach out to the other communities

00:16:39.810 --> 00:16:45.670
because the
question was if my daughter is not cut, she

00:16:45.670 --> 00:16:49.240
won't be able to get
married because it's a cultural expectation.

00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:53.990
And so they had to begin to work in groups
of communities to really get

00:16:53.990 --> 00:17:01.350
impact on this practice.
Now, there are over 4,000 communities now

00:17:01.350 --> 00:17:03.680
in Senegal that have
abandoned as a result of this community-based

00:17:03.680 --> 00:17:06.159
approach.
And so I think we now know what the formula

00:17:06.159 --> 00:17:07.159
is that works.

00:17:07.159 --> 00:17:10.409
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: And just to push a little
harder.

00:17:10.409 --> 00:17:15.780
I mean, it is fair to say that the previous
campaign really since the

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:21.569
1970s, these laws passed, conferences held
 -- I was in Guinea last year

00:17:21.569 --> 00:17:27.059
where FGM is punishable by life imprisonment
on the part of the

00:17:27.059 --> 00:17:31.389
parents, or in some cases if the girl dies,
actually by execution.

00:17:31.389 --> 00:17:35.110
And yet, 99 percent of Guinean girls are still
cut.

00:17:35.110 --> 00:17:39.669
I mean, given the need to learn from mistakes,
is it fair to say that

00:17:39.669 --> 00:17:44.870
that long campaign, until the more community-based
approach of Tostan,

00:17:44.870 --> 00:17:49.210
really is a failure that we should learn from?
And I'll toss that out to anybody.

00:17:49.210 --> 00:17:54.759
I don't mean to subject Ann to -- to this.
But, I mean you're welcome to address that

00:17:54.759 --> 00:17:56.260
Ann or anybody else can jump
in.

00:17:56.260 --> 00:18:00.441
ANN VENEMAN: I think, I mean I think this
is one of the consequences

00:18:00.441 --> 00:18:05.759
is that, you know, people don't want to be
told what to do particularly

00:18:05.759 --> 00:18:09.649
when they believe it's part of their culture
that has been around for

00:18:09.649 --> 00:18:12.970
generations.
On the other hand, one of the countries with

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:16.940
the highest prevalence of
female genital cutting is Egypt.

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:21.279
And they have, particularly with some of the
women in the country

00:18:21.279 --> 00:18:25.710
speaking out themselves, some of the local
women, some of the leaders

00:18:25.710 --> 00:18:29.870
including the First Lady speaking out on these
issues, they're finding

00:18:29.870 --> 00:18:33.860
that they can have an impact particularly
as more and more women get

00:18:33.860 --> 00:18:36.940
access or more and more families get access
to television.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:41.399
So they can address some of these issues on
things like soap operas or

00:18:41.399 --> 00:18:45.970
other ways of communicating with women on
television to begin a little

00:18:45.970 --> 00:18:49.429
bit more dialogue about whether or not this
is really something that

00:18:49.429 --> 00:18:52.530
has to be continued in the culture or whether
or not it can be changed.

00:18:52.530 --> 00:18:58.280
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: And I think as well,
Nick, that the absolute

00:18:58.280 --> 00:19:02.830
importance of a multilevel approach, so the
community grassroots level

00:19:02.830 --> 00:19:06.639
work is absolutely vital.
But unless, as you say, the legislation is

00:19:06.639 --> 00:19:11.320
there, unless legislation is
enforced, unless there's allied advocacy,

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:16.519
a media campaign's coming in
to tell people about the changes in law.

00:19:16.519 --> 00:19:22.870
Recently, Uganda outlawed FGM, but there's
a criticism there that

00:19:22.870 --> 00:19:25.970
governments done very little to actually tell
people within Uganda that

00:19:25.970 --> 00:19:30.659
it's illegal.
So you need an approach across the board that

00:19:30.659 --> 00:19:32.300
is there to reinforce
this message.

00:19:32.300 --> 00:19:36.830
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: And Julia, there's a question
here that from a

00:19:36.830 --> 00:19:43.269
YouTube viewer, um, and I wondered if you
could answer it while raising

00:19:43.269 --> 00:19:47.600
some of the consequences, the practical consequences,
in terms of

00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:51.990
health sexual assault whatever it may be.
Mitch from London says if you could spend

00:19:51.990 --> 00:19:54.280
five minutes with a
grandmother of a girl that was about to be

00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:58.309
cut, presumably the
grandmother being -- the assumption is grandmother

00:19:58.309 --> 00:20:00.490
is the decisionmaker
there, if you could spend five minutes with

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:05.179
a grandmother of a girl who
was about to cut, what would you say?

00:20:05.179 --> 00:20:06.179
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: You know the first thing
 --

00:20:06.179 --> 00:20:08.090
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: And actually if -- maybe
let's pretend Mitch didn't

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:10.679
say five-minutes, let's say one minute.

00:20:10.679 --> 00:20:13.460
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: Okay.
Not five minutes.

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:19.169
Actually first of all I'd listen.
I'm volunteering in this area and I know as

00:20:19.169 --> 00:20:22.779
Larry was talking about
this charge of cultural imperialism coming

00:20:22.779 --> 00:20:26.330
in changing communities.
I cannot sit in front of a grandmother and

00:20:26.330 --> 00:20:31.009
leap in and tell her why
this is wrong.

00:20:31.009 --> 00:20:37.850
But what I can do is talk about health impacts,
as Ann said, the causal

00:20:37.850 --> 00:20:44.519
links between what happens in FGM, and then
the constant infections,

00:20:44.519 --> 00:20:50.619
the sepsis, the childbirth complications,
everything that results are

00:20:50.619 --> 00:20:54.059
not known often because the girls are cut
at such a young age.

00:20:54.059 --> 00:20:57.090
So they don't realize that the impacts that
this has.

00:20:57.090 --> 00:21:02.360
And in fact, many circumcisers are the greatest
advocates within their

00:21:02.360 --> 00:21:06.770
own community to say why this must end, once
they've seen it.

00:21:06.770 --> 00:21:12.259
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Larry, your -- you and your
organization are

00:21:12.259 --> 00:21:19.950
obviously focused on human rights.
And if a -- um, what -- has the human rights

00:21:19.950 --> 00:21:27.350
community been sort of
slow to look, to focus on some of these broad

00:21:27.350 --> 00:21:29.540
issues that involve every
home?

00:21:29.540 --> 00:21:33.760
In other words if a -- if a Sudanese dissident
gets arrested by the

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:38.200
government, then obviously everybody writes
letters.

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:43.600
If 3 million girls a year get cut, then you
know, whether it's

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:47.539
organizations, whether it's we in the media,
everybody -- that people

00:21:47.539 --> 00:21:50.040
kind of tune out.

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:52.539
LARRY COX: Yeah.
There's no doubt about that.

00:21:52.539 --> 00:21:56.430
We have been too slow.
And it's a sort of painful history to have

00:21:56.430 --> 00:21:57.619
to look at.
To understand not only the importance of this

00:21:57.619 --> 00:22:03.490
issue but the important
general of the rights of women as key not

00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:07.110
only to women but to in fact
the advancement of all human rights.

00:22:07.110 --> 00:22:10.490
And it really was the Women's Movement that
pushed the human rights

00:22:10.490 --> 00:22:16.340
community to begin to understand this.
And as it did, our work on all human rights

00:22:16.340 --> 00:22:21.410
began to improve because
the lessons that you've learned about FGM

00:22:21.410 --> 00:22:25.240
are lessons that in fact
apply to other human rights violations as

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:26.740
well.
That you have to work with the community,

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:29.320
that you have to understand,
you have to listen, that you have to empower

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:32.919
the people who are there
and you also understand that in this issue,

00:22:32.919 --> 00:22:38.700
it's not simply a question
of -- of this issue separate from the larger

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:42.240
issue of violence against
women and the larger issue of the devaluation

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:44.090
of women, of the
discrimination against women.

00:22:44.090 --> 00:22:47.740
I don't think you can really solve -- and
Tostan certainly took this

00:22:47.740 --> 00:22:50.090
approach the reason it adopted a human rights
approach was because

00:22:50.090 --> 00:22:55.080
human rights speak across-the-board.
That has a holistic vision of what people

00:22:55.080 --> 00:22:57.279
need.
It's not just issue-oriented, but it's issued

00:22:57.279 --> 00:22:59.139
on the basic rights that
everyone needs.

00:22:59.139 --> 00:23:02.519
And when it did that, the community began
to understand this not as a

00:23:02.519 --> 00:23:06.240
isolated cultural practice that everyone condemned
by as part of

00:23:06.240 --> 00:23:10.789
general fight for the human rights of everybody
in the community.

00:23:10.789 --> 00:23:14.200
And I think that made a difference.
But we have learned a lot.

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:18.259
And we need to keep learning.
I think now, I'm proud to say, that certainly

00:23:18.259 --> 00:23:23.909
my own organization has
made the rights of women central, central

00:23:23.909 --> 00:23:25.769
to its work on human rights.

00:23:25.769 --> 00:23:28.730
KATHY CALVIN: And I would just add where the
UN is on the ground

00:23:28.730 --> 00:23:32.870
dealing with this, whether it's UNICEF or
UNFPA, the population fund,

00:23:32.870 --> 00:23:36.630
or UNIFEM, the approach is actually a very
holistic one where they're

00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:40.090
trying to keep the girls in school and take
care of all the other

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:43.659
issues that change both the culture of the
community, and the girls'

00:23:43.659 --> 00:23:48.409
own aspirations for her life, in effect, empowering
her.

00:23:48.409 --> 00:23:51.950
But the cutting takes place at such an early
age, you have to deal

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:55.029
with, then, the mothers and the fathers and
the whole community.

00:23:55.029 --> 00:23:58.340
So the girl doesn't become an advocate for
herself until it's too late.

00:23:58.340 --> 00:24:02.029
I find it interesting that, you know, there's
roughly 28 countries in

00:24:02.029 --> 00:24:06.570
which it's prevalent still.
19 of them have laws against it, it is criminal,

00:24:06.570 --> 00:24:08.700
criminalized in those
countries.

00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:11.580
But that's only half, and even in those countries,
we're still fighting

00:24:11.580 --> 00:24:14.549
this battle.
So there is a rule of law problem here that

00:24:14.549 --> 00:24:16.029
I'm sure you're dealing
with as well.

00:24:16.029 --> 00:24:21.840
That it -- that's not the only answer obviously.
You need -- you need these groups in there

00:24:21.840 --> 00:24:26.149
trying to change the culture
at the group level.

00:24:26.149 --> 00:24:27.789
LARRY COX: And it's also important to point
out it's not a problem

00:24:27.789 --> 00:24:30.870
that just confined to Africa or -- I mean,
it's now around the world.

00:24:30.870 --> 00:24:36.429
It's in Europe; it's in the United States.
And that even makes it even more complicated

00:24:36.429 --> 00:24:40.539
to talk about how you're
going to -- to stop it.

00:24:40.539 --> 00:24:45.300
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Well, that actually goes
to a question here from Rob

00:24:45.300 --> 00:24:54.289
from Loos, which is think is in the UK, asks,
"You and others have

00:24:54.289 --> 00:24:56.749
talked about the need to stop FGM within a
generation.

00:24:56.749 --> 00:24:58.040
Do you really think you can do it?"
Kathy?

00:24:58.040 --> 00:25:01.909
KATHY CALVIN: Well, there's a goal that the
UN has set that to

00:25:01.909 --> 00:25:04.940
eliminate by 2015, which is the date for the
millennium development

00:25:04.940 --> 00:25:06.950
goals.
I don't think there's any real we shouldn't

00:25:06.950 --> 00:25:10.590
be trying for that.
That's far enough away that we could really

00:25:10.590 --> 00:25:15.309
do a concerted effort and
frankly, it's going to take a global campaign,

00:25:15.309 --> 00:25:17.379
you know.
And we need a global campaign for girls.

00:25:17.379 --> 00:25:19.690
This ought to be right front and center at
the beginning of it.

00:25:19.690 --> 00:25:20.760
So I think it's doable.

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:24.450
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: So there's a -- there may
be a parallel with China.

00:25:24.450 --> 00:25:27.639
Foot binding was actually punishable by exile
on the part of

00:25:27.639 --> 00:25:30.769
the parents -- had zero impact.
At various points, it was banned.

00:25:30.769 --> 00:25:34.369
No impact.
And then early in the 20th century, really

00:25:34.369 --> 00:25:37.480
remarkable quickly, it
disappeared.

00:25:37.480 --> 00:25:41.600
And it went from a perception on the part
of parents that if they

00:25:41.600 --> 00:25:43.909
didn't bind their daughter's feet, that it
would be hard for her to

00:25:43.909 --> 00:25:47.200
marry, to a perception that if they bound
her feet, it would be harder

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:51.980
for her to get married.
And, um, it, you know, I guess that --

00:25:51.980 --> 00:25:57.299
KATHY CALVIN: One emperor changed the rule,
changed the perception.

00:25:57.299 --> 00:26:02.299
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: It was a really a bottom-up
social movement, um, led

00:26:02.299 --> 00:26:08.379
by elites from within the country, um, part
of this sense of awakening.

00:26:08.379 --> 00:26:12.869
And supported by outsiders to some degree
but -- but really led from

00:26:12.869 --> 00:26:18.999
within, pushed from within.
So I guess the question is how we can replicate

00:26:18.999 --> 00:26:22.649
that, and whether
groups like Tostan are indeed -- whether this

00:26:22.649 --> 00:26:27.389
is the next sort of foot
binding analogy, so that the change once it

00:26:27.389 --> 00:26:30.320
comes you've reached the
tipping point, it will happen very, very quickly.

00:26:30.320 --> 00:26:33.529
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: I just want to come
back to that point Kathy

00:26:33.529 --> 00:26:38.850
made of 2015.
I wished I shared your optimism, Kathy.

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:43.330
I just feel that we're here talking about
solutions.

00:26:43.330 --> 00:26:47.340
We seem to know what works.
We know this model is there.

00:26:47.340 --> 00:26:51.100
We know about the respect we have to give
to communities.

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:56.919
Um, and many, many local NGOs and civil society
organizations are

00:26:56.919 --> 00:27:02.470
working on the ground, and you know to pay
tribute to all of those

00:27:02.470 --> 00:27:08.169
small organizations really at danger as well.
One of the women who's contacted me through

00:27:08.169 --> 00:27:12.739
this campaign, Lucy Maswa,
who said, you know, go forth and speak at

00:27:12.739 --> 00:27:17.409
Davos about this.
And her story, once she started speaking out

00:27:17.409 --> 00:27:21.669
within her community, she
was raped, she was beaten, she was tied to

00:27:21.669 --> 00:27:27.260
a tree, she was jailed.
She's luckily living now in the US.

00:27:27.260 --> 00:27:34.519
But I think what we need to see is how we
can in the next five years,

00:27:34.519 --> 00:27:39.489
if that is true, take this to scale -- I'm
using the language of Davos

00:27:39.489 --> 00:27:45.399
there -- but really, you know, what is preventing
us if we know how to

00:27:45.399 --> 00:27:50.629
make things change, why can't we put this
into place?

00:27:50.629 --> 00:27:54.289
It is a funding issue?
It is a global awareness issue?

00:27:54.289 --> 00:27:57.570
What needs to happen?
What are the levers that we can pull?

00:27:57.570 --> 00:28:02.129
If we were sitting here saying actually this
is to intractable; this is

00:28:02.129 --> 00:28:05.090
too difficult.
We're not going to address this issue.

00:28:05.090 --> 00:28:08.499
Fair enough.
But we're all sitting here in vehement agreement

00:28:08.499 --> 00:28:12.909
that is a severe
abuse, a child's right abuse, a women's right

00:28:12.909 --> 00:28:15.230
abuse.
We've got a solution.

00:28:15.230 --> 00:28:16.679
What can we do?

00:28:16.679 --> 00:28:20.909
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: A bunch people from on YouTube
asked variations of

00:28:20.909 --> 00:28:26.759
that, you know, what have we learned from
 -- from, well, one person

00:28:26.759 --> 00:28:29.720
asked what have we learned from HIV campaigns
that can be transposed

00:28:29.720 --> 00:28:33.240
into working to eradicate FGM, various other
people asked, you know,

00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:37.429
variations of that.
But Ann, given what you talked about earlier,

00:28:37.429 --> 00:28:43.780
isn't indeed one lesson
perhaps that a bunch of outsiders, at the

00:28:43.780 --> 00:28:49.299
treetops, the top-down
efforts on their own aren't going to get very

00:28:49.299 --> 00:28:54.899
far and that what does
work is outsiders supporting indigenous efforts

00:28:54.899 --> 00:28:59.669
from within the
culture, and giving them the microphone and

00:28:59.669 --> 00:29:02.029
us standing back and
letting them lead the way.

00:29:02.029 --> 00:29:04.191
I mean, is that -- is that part of it?

00:29:04.191 --> 00:29:07.129
ANN VENEMAN: Well, I absolutely think it's
part of it.

00:29:07.129 --> 00:29:13.619
I think that if you can't change the norms,
the practices of

00:29:13.619 --> 00:29:19.419
communities unless you listen and understand
and have a dialogue.

00:29:19.419 --> 00:29:24.909
And again the Tostan approach did exactly
that, listened to the why,

00:29:24.909 --> 00:29:29.850
listened to the perceptions.
And then also gave information about the health

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:35.080
effects, the facts.
I think that's one of the things that we haven't

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:39.789
done enough of as an
international community around a number of

00:29:39.789 --> 00:29:43.370
these issues.
And you mentioned HIV/AIDS, you know, one

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:48.110
of the most difficult things,
we've gotten better coverage of prevention

00:29:48.110 --> 00:29:52.409
of mother-to-child
transmission, of treatment of AIDS generally,

00:29:52.409 --> 00:29:56.929
of treatment of pediatric
AIDS -- one of the most difficult things has

00:29:56.929 --> 00:30:03.379
been to understand how to
have an impact with education.

00:30:03.379 --> 00:30:07.529
It just hasn't seemed to work.
And part of it is, I don't think we understand

00:30:07.529 --> 00:30:10.450
and listen to
communities enough.

00:30:10.450 --> 00:30:17.919
For example, you know, one of the things that
you talk about in

00:30:17.919 --> 00:30:21.480
Southern Africa where AIDS is most prevalent
is use of condoms.

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:27.299
But there are practices in places like Swaziland,
where in order to get

00:30:27.299 --> 00:30:31.320
married, you have to get pregnant first to
show your fertility.

00:30:31.320 --> 00:30:35.200
Well, it's a little difficult to talk about
using condoms when you want

00:30:35.200 --> 00:30:39.590
to get pregnant.
And so, I think, if you don't listen to the

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:44.549
community and understand
the whys, the -- how the practices work and

00:30:44.549 --> 00:30:48.460
what's going on truly in
the communities and have a dialogue about

00:30:48.460 --> 00:30:50.620
it, you can't actually make
the change.

00:30:50.620 --> 00:30:55.070
And I think this, this human rights approach,
engaging the community in

00:30:55.070 --> 00:30:59.659
human rights, in women's rights, in men and
women understanding each

00:30:59.659 --> 00:31:03.570
other and why things are happening is a way
to really make an impact in

00:31:03.570 --> 00:31:06.419
changing some of these practices, particularly
those that are most

00:31:06.419 --> 00:31:07.549
harmful for women.

00:31:07.549 --> 00:31:08.690
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Larry?

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:12.450
LARRY COX: If I could just -- because I don't
want to create a sort of

00:31:12.450 --> 00:31:17.269
dichotomy between the approach that you just
described, which I fully

00:31:17.269 --> 00:31:19.794
support, and the idea of outside pressure
because that can lead to a

00:31:19.794 --> 00:31:22.950
kind of paralysis on the part of people who
aren't able to have a

00:31:22.950 --> 00:31:26.950
dialogue with the community.
And I think the lesson not only on this issue

00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:30.859
but on many, many other
issues is as Julia said you need a multilevel

00:31:30.859 --> 00:31:34.749
or multifaceted kind of
approach.

00:31:34.749 --> 00:31:37.559
Because I think to take your China example,
which is really

00:31:37.559 --> 00:31:42.509
fascinating, which I want to like learn to
use more -- there was also

00:31:42.509 --> 00:31:46.419
very, very strong political will on the part
of the government that

00:31:46.419 --> 00:31:50.859
played a major role I think, as I understand
it.

00:31:50.859 --> 00:31:55.059
At least I'm thinking about --

00:31:55.059 --> 00:31:59.139
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: I actually -- I think at
previous points there was

00:31:59.139 --> 00:32:02.970
central political will that actually didn't
really get anywhere.

00:32:02.970 --> 00:32:07.640
And at the time when foot binding really ended
up being eradicated you

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:09.940
had very weak central governments that --

00:32:09.940 --> 00:32:12.879
LARRY COX: All right.
I was thinking it happened after the Revolution.

00:32:12.879 --> 00:32:14.679
But it happened before?

00:32:14.679 --> 00:32:19.550
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Well, it began happening
before and the end of the

00:32:19.550 --> 00:32:25.679
Ching Dynasty and then after that in a period
when you had real social

00:32:25.679 --> 00:32:28.809
awakening but pretty fragile central governments.

00:32:28.809 --> 00:32:33.519
LARRY COX: Well, at any rate, my point is
that I think you need to

00:32:33.519 --> 00:32:37.909
put -- we need to put pressure on governments
to not simply pass laws,

00:32:37.909 --> 00:32:43.769
which is the easy thing to do, but to actually
not allow the kinds of

00:32:43.769 --> 00:32:47.779
practices that Julia talked about.
I mean it's -- you know, where people are

00:32:47.779 --> 00:32:50.302
being threatened.
People are -- lives are in danger, you need,

00:32:50.302 --> 00:32:57.119
the outside world needs to
be in support in a very practical way of people

00:32:57.119 --> 00:33:02.250
who are speaking out
and who are being threatened as a result of

00:33:02.250 --> 00:33:05.210
speaking out on this issue
as well as on other women's rights issues.

00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:10.220
So I don't think it's an either/or thing.
I think that we need very much to correct

00:33:10.220 --> 00:33:15.270
what I think is a
longstanding failure to appreciate the community

00:33:15.270 --> 00:33:17.190
approach.
But I also think we still need to keep --

00:33:17.190 --> 00:33:20.759
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Let me press you on that
a little further since you

00:33:20.759 --> 00:33:27.249
have an -- a Y chromosome here.
And I think there might be some men watching

00:33:27.249 --> 00:33:33.039
whether here or on YouTube
who will think hey, you know, this isn't my

00:33:33.039 --> 00:33:36.610
fight.
I don't have a clitoris.

00:33:36.610 --> 00:33:40.690
And what end -- and the same thing, I think,
applies to a lot of other

00:33:40.690 --> 00:33:44.700
women's rights issues.
Um, what do you say to them?

00:33:44.700 --> 00:33:45.700
Is this their fight or not?

00:33:45.700 --> 00:33:51.409
LARRY COX: Oh, absolutely, it is their fight.
If they care at all about human rights, about

00:33:51.409 --> 00:33:53.210
their own freedom, and
their own dignity.

00:33:53.210 --> 00:33:58.019
I mean, I think that was my point about the
linkage between the fight

00:33:58.019 --> 00:34:00.049
for women's rights and the fight for all human
rights.

00:34:00.049 --> 00:34:07.210
I mean, it's not -- we all can very easily
draw the connections between

00:34:07.210 --> 00:34:12.159
the status of women in any particular society
and the general status of

00:34:12.159 --> 00:34:15.409
human rights in that society.
And that includes the societies in which many

00:34:15.409 --> 00:34:24.280
of the people who are
watching this, um, discussion live.

00:34:24.280 --> 00:34:29.700
Insofar as -- and it's the experience of my
own, my own life and my own

00:34:29.700 --> 00:34:35.760
organization that it was the struggle of women
for their rights that

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:40.149
made us understand our own, our own rights
and the way things are

00:34:40.149 --> 00:34:44.049
connected, and the way that -- the approach
we were taking was a

00:34:44.049 --> 00:34:52.159
very narrow and very limited approach.
So I think it's in the vital interest of every

00:34:52.159 --> 00:34:55.649
man.
And we, of course, don't live in isolation

00:34:55.649 --> 00:35:00.000
from women.
You know, we have daughters, we have wives,

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:04.430
we have lovers.
We -- you know, it's inconceivable to me that

00:35:04.430 --> 00:35:07.730
someone could say this is
not of any interest to me because I'm male

00:35:07.730 --> 00:35:10.839
and this happens to women,
anymore than I would expect women to say,

00:35:10.839 --> 00:35:13.770
I'm not really interested in
what happened to Nelson Mandela because he's

00:35:13.770 --> 00:35:17.470
a man and I'm a woman.
I mean what kind of world is that where we

00:35:17.470 --> 00:35:19.789
suddenly divide our
feelings?

00:35:19.789 --> 00:35:22.540
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Maybe one more way of thinking
about it is that the

00:35:22.540 --> 00:35:25.390
Holocaust wasn't
a Jewish issue civil rights weren't a black

00:35:25.390 --> 00:35:28.230
issue and FGM isn't just a
women's issue.

00:35:28.230 --> 00:35:29.230
LARRY COX: Right. Exactly.

00:35:29.230 --> 00:35:33.369
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: And I think particularly,
men play such a huge

00:35:33.369 --> 00:35:37.400
part in the communities that practice this
as Ann has said because one

00:35:37.400 --> 00:35:42.410
of the key reasons for FGM being in place
is it makes a girl marriageable.

00:35:42.410 --> 00:35:46.170
And when, as part of these community conversations,
the men come

00:35:46.170 --> 00:35:52.109
together and decide that they will marry an
uncut woman, this is how it

00:35:52.109 --> 00:35:55.930
changes within a generation.
And you then move though to the next community

00:35:55.930 --> 00:35:58.160
which is the
intra-marrying group.

00:35:58.160 --> 00:36:02.089
So men are so vital in this debate and particularly
as religious

00:36:02.089 --> 00:36:03.089
leaders as well.

00:36:03.089 --> 00:36:07.270
KATHY CALVIN: And I think when we focus on
rights, we get stuck.

00:36:07.270 --> 00:36:10.530
When we focus on economics, which is really
what this all comes down to

00:36:10.530 --> 00:36:14.680
is kind of what's a girl worth and is this
about marrying her for her

00:36:14.680 --> 00:36:19.520
value -- it changes.
I think because it's girls, people do react

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:22.109
differently than women.
So I think that's going to help bring more

00:36:22.109 --> 00:36:26.490
people to the issue.
We've used economic incentives in a number

00:36:26.490 --> 00:36:30.369
of cases to get communities
to think differently about early marriage.

00:36:30.369 --> 00:36:34.410
And the consequence of the man finally having
a reason to stop and

00:36:34.410 --> 00:36:38.910
think about his daughter marrying early or
marrying late, when there's

00:36:38.910 --> 00:36:43.930
an economic incentive to do so.
And in the case, in Ethiopia, a girl who stays

00:36:43.930 --> 00:36:48.960
in school is eligible
for a sheep or a goat for her family if she

00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:50.270
stays in school two more
years.

00:36:50.270 --> 00:36:56.359
The fathers have been saying, hmmm, I wasn't
really in the conversation

00:36:56.359 --> 00:36:58.309
before.
I had no reason to have the conversation.

00:36:58.309 --> 00:37:01.440
I had no reason to think about it.
I had no reason to think about the value my

00:37:01.440 --> 00:37:05.170
daughter could bring to my
family if she stayed in school longer.

00:37:05.170 --> 00:37:11.540
The economic incentive got him to pay attention.
So I'm for the hybrid solution, which is the

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:16.030
community, the listening,
incentives where we can -- where we can apply

00:37:16.030 --> 00:37:17.819
them.
And I know not everybody loves incentives

00:37:17.819 --> 00:37:22.339
but I think they work and the
external pressure.

00:37:22.339 --> 00:37:26.240
but I think rights sometimes gets people into
the different kind of

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:29.241
conversation where we have -- we have a different
view of rights.

00:37:29.241 --> 00:37:31.990
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Speaking of a different
kind of conversation, we've

00:37:31.990 --> 00:37:34.750
been -- we've been discussing at one level.
But I want to kind of make it real.

00:37:34.750 --> 00:37:41.920
And we have a video clip from Mali, and I
have not yet seen it.

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:46.020
I'm briefed that everybody in the history
who has ever seen it has

00:37:46.020 --> 00:37:49.579
promptly burst into tears afterward so pull
out your handkerchiefs.

00:37:49.579 --> 00:38:13.490
But if we can role that, that would be great.

00:38:13.490 --> 00:38:27.410
[VIDEO PLAYING]

00:38:27.410 --> 00:38:41.339
[CHILDREN CRYING]

00:38:41.339 --> 00:39:49.660
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Well, that goes a zillion
times a day in much of the

00:39:49.660 --> 00:39:54.059
world.
And, um, I don't know exactly what kind of

00:39:54.059 --> 00:39:59.760
cutting this was, but it did
not appear to be infibulation which is the

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:04.859
much worse kind.
And in that case, the girls' legs are afterward

00:40:04.859 --> 00:40:10.260
often tied together,
and for a couple weeks or so the wound can

00:40:10.260 --> 00:40:20.029
heal.
And is, you know, is that squared.

00:40:20.029 --> 00:40:26.849
Jennifer, I'm sorry, Jane, from the UK asks
how can women fight GM in

00:40:26.849 --> 00:40:32.779
cultures where they have no voice?
And likewise, Sam from Devin says FGM seems

00:40:32.779 --> 00:40:36.690
to be about what women in
some cultures believe they must do and be,

00:40:36.690 --> 00:40:39.960
to have value to the men who
hold power.

00:40:39.960 --> 00:40:42.240
If we're to change the thinking of men and
women in these cultures what

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:44.140
can we draw from our own experience to guide
us?

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:47.859
And let me put out this -- frame that to the
panel.

00:40:47.859 --> 00:40:52.220
I mean, I think that there's a perception
that this is often really

00:40:52.220 --> 00:40:55.960
about men oppressing women, and it seems to
me at least that it's much

00:40:55.960 --> 00:41:01.430
more complicated than that.
And typically, this is what women, in fact,

00:41:01.430 --> 00:41:06.430
are doing to other women.
That the men, they may want to marry a girl

00:41:06.430 --> 00:41:09.289
who's cut but they're
largely removed from the decision making.

00:41:09.289 --> 00:41:12.760
And in fact, partly because men are more likely
to be educated they --

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:18.420
it seems quite plausible to me that men are
more likely to be against

00:41:18.420 --> 00:41:24.089
FGM than women are in these countries.
I don't know any survey but that, anecdotally,

00:41:24.089 --> 00:41:26.549
I wouldn't be surprised
if that's the case.

00:41:26.549 --> 00:41:32.440
So I wonder if the problem, you know, isn't
often patriarchal values

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:37.140
even misogynistic values, that are absorbed
and transmitted as much by

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:40.690
women as by men, you know, if that isn't a
better way of looking at

00:41:40.690 --> 00:41:42.630
this than men oppressing women.

00:41:42.630 --> 00:41:48.950
KATHY CALVIN: Well, and the video just showed
women are the primary

00:41:48.950 --> 00:41:52.920
carriers of the culture.
I mean, Ann, you've probably -- because you've

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:55.430
seen it, you know, that
is the way it's passed on.

00:41:55.430 --> 00:41:59.590
And you may have a point of view on that but
that's how it -- it is

00:41:59.590 --> 00:42:00.661
carried into the community.

00:42:00.661 --> 00:42:08.289
ANN VENEMAN: Well, I think that, I mean, certainly
that clip showed

00:42:08.289 --> 00:42:13.400
that it is practiced -- when it's actually
done, it's women who cut the

00:42:13.400 --> 00:42:19.910
girls.
And -- but yet, it is the men who were saying

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:24.109
my daughter will not be
able to get married if she's not cut.

00:42:24.109 --> 00:42:30.059
So I think it's -- it's a practice, it's a
culture that has to be

00:42:30.059 --> 00:42:33.020
addressed as a whole not -- it's not just
women.

00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:36.559
It's not just men.
It's everybody's responsibility to kind of

00:42:36.559 --> 00:42:38.450
look at how this is going to
change.

00:42:38.450 --> 00:42:44.089
Now having said that, it is not the same -- it's
not practiced the same

00:42:44.089 --> 00:42:50.680
in every country.
I went a year before last to Sierra Leone.

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:55.630
I was reading my briefing papers and I find
out female genital cutting

00:42:55.630 --> 00:43:02.410
is quite prevalent in Sierra Leon.
So I call up Molly Melching, who founded Tostan,

00:43:02.410 --> 00:43:04.579
and I said, what are
you doing in Sierra Leone?

00:43:04.579 --> 00:43:07.640
And she said, we're not because it's completely
different.

00:43:07.640 --> 00:43:15.299
They practice something called secret societies.
And secret societies are where girls would

00:43:15.299 --> 00:43:20.619
go before there was an
education system, they would go off for maybe

00:43:20.619 --> 00:43:25.170
a few months at a time
and they would learn how to be a wife.

00:43:25.170 --> 00:43:27.839
They'd learn how to do all of these different
things.

00:43:27.839 --> 00:43:32.880
This was their education.
And part of it was, they got cut.

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:38.160
Now those secret societies still exist in
Sierra Leone and still a

00:43:38.160 --> 00:43:42.119
number of young girls get cut, although less
and less.

00:43:42.119 --> 00:43:45.940
And the secret societies are much less about
going for a long period of

00:43:45.940 --> 00:43:51.549
time and more just about cutting now.
But one of the things I found when I was there,

00:43:51.549 --> 00:43:57.540
is that young teenage
girls who were still in school were talking

00:43:57.540 --> 00:44:02.150
about these secret
societies and these practices as things that

00:44:02.150 --> 00:44:06.079
they were going to try to
help be a part of the past.

00:44:06.079 --> 00:44:11.180
And so I think there is some ability to engage
in some of these kinds

00:44:11.180 --> 00:44:17.410
of communities, again, the practices are different.
And in that country, it's -- it's done in

00:44:17.410 --> 00:44:20.210
a completely different way.
So I think it's again, it's about listening,

00:44:20.210 --> 00:44:23.940
it's about learning.
Learning about the particular culture and

00:44:23.940 --> 00:44:26.589
practices of a country and
the history of it.

00:44:26.589 --> 00:44:29.990
I think is key to finding the way to eliminate
it.

00:44:29.990 --> 00:44:33.380
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Speaking of culture and
practices I mean another

00:44:33.380 --> 00:44:40.520
layer of complexity here is frankly religion.
That there -- and I want to be very clear

00:44:40.520 --> 00:44:48.049
here -- a great part of the
Muslim world does not practice cutting.

00:44:48.049 --> 00:44:54.180
There's nothing in the Qur'an about cutting.
In the Arabian peninsula, almost nobody does

00:44:54.180 --> 00:45:00.369
any cutting.
And there are also a number of Christian places,

00:45:00.369 --> 00:45:03.279
Ethiopia, in
particular.

00:45:03.279 --> 00:45:08.039
In fact in Ethiopia, Christians do some of
the most severe cutting.

00:45:08.039 --> 00:45:13.819
All that said, most of the cutting occurs
in Muslim countries, whether

00:45:13.819 --> 00:45:20.349
that is in Africa or in Asia.
And doesn't that -- I mean, given the problems

00:45:20.349 --> 00:45:25.069
right now between the
West and the Muslim world, doesn't that create

00:45:25.069 --> 00:45:31.960
one more layer of
complexity if you have Western efforts to

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:36.190
go against a practice that is
disproportionately embedded in the Muslim

00:45:36.190 --> 00:45:41.170
world?
And I don't know who I want to hand this nice,

00:45:41.170 --> 00:45:43.190
this potato to.

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:51.920
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: Can I turn it around
and just say Mauritania has

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:59.099
just issued a fatwa against FGM.
34 Islamic leaders have actually just said

00:45:59.099 --> 00:46:05.079
that this is absolutely not
in the Qur'an and not an issue.

00:46:05.079 --> 00:46:09.730
I hate to address the positives in the debate,
but you know there is

00:46:09.730 --> 00:46:12.619
change.
And at least if we know that this is one of

00:46:12.619 --> 00:46:15.089
the key issues, at least we
can begin to address it.

00:46:15.089 --> 00:46:19.160
LARRY COX: I think one of the things that
has changed that we need to

00:46:19.160 --> 00:46:24.079
not keep acting as if it hasn't changed is
that, you know, human rights

00:46:24.079 --> 00:46:27.260
issues are no longer a concern of the West
somehow.

00:46:27.260 --> 00:46:31.900
And the human rights movement is no longer
located in the West.

00:46:31.900 --> 00:46:34.579
It's everywhere.
There are human rights organizations, there

00:46:34.579 --> 00:46:37.200
are thousands of human
rights organizations in virtually every region.

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:41.819
And in the Muslim world there are incredible
organizations and fighters

00:46:41.819 --> 00:46:45.119
for human rights.
And I think what has to shift is that we need

00:46:45.119 --> 00:46:47.230
to see -- this is
something my organization has to struggle

00:46:47.230 --> 00:46:51.700
with -- is how do we shift
our role from being sort of the saviors of

00:46:51.700 --> 00:46:55.619
the world that savior
paradigm to a role of like really empowering

00:46:55.619 --> 00:46:59.520
and trying to help and
listen to those organizations in those cultures

00:46:59.520 --> 00:47:02.049
who are fighting.
There is an incredible struggle, which we

00:47:02.049 --> 00:47:04.970
often don't publicize very
much, we don't write about it very much, we

00:47:04.970 --> 00:47:10.539
act as if it's not there
within Islam, within the Muslim world, on

00:47:10.539 --> 00:47:12.940
these issues, on what it
means.

00:47:12.940 --> 00:47:16.349
And that's the struggle, I think, which is
ultimately going to

00:47:16.349 --> 00:47:20.500
determine the success for the reasons we gave
about when human rights

00:47:20.500 --> 00:47:25.740
succeed, it's because they're rooted in the
indigenous struggle; in the

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:28.660
culture, and that's what I think is the hope
for this.

00:47:28.660 --> 00:47:32.960
That's it becoming a global issue not a Western
issue being imposed on

00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:36.660
the part of the world that carries it out,
which was the model decades

00:47:36.660 --> 00:47:37.660
ago.

00:47:37.660 --> 00:47:41.480
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: Marion from Germany asks
what do you think should be

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:44.359
the punishment levelled by the international
community for nations that

00:47:44.359 --> 00:47:50.000
permit FGM?
Um, now I don't -- my hunch is probably none

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:55.970
of you think countries as
such should be punished but, why not?

00:47:55.970 --> 00:48:00.150
I mean there are levers that we can apply
to countries to take this

00:48:00.150 --> 00:48:02.770
issue more seriously?
Or would that create a backlash that would

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:03.770
be unhelpful?

00:48:03.770 --> 00:48:08.340
JULIA LALLA-MAHARAJH: It's already there in
the Maputo Protocol, which

00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:13.160
has been signed up to by many African states,
but not yet ratified.

00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:17.859
So absolutely we have role to play as an international
community to get

00:48:17.859 --> 00:48:23.260
some of these issues enshrined in law.
And, you know, we had a conversation about

00:48:23.260 --> 00:48:27.260
CEDAW, the -- elimination
of -- sorry.

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:30.950
The Commission for the Elimination of Discrimination
Against Women --

00:48:30.950 --> 00:48:37.019
trips off the tongue, you know, all of these
levers do play an

00:48:37.019 --> 00:48:40.500
important part, I think.
And we need to keep the pressure up to ensure

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:41.540
that they're ratified.

00:48:41.540 --> 00:48:44.671
NICHOLAS KRISTOF: CEDAW has been, of course,
passed by a hundred and

00:48:44.671 --> 00:48:49.309
-- I don't know how many countries, and one
of the very few that has

00:48:49.309 --> 00:48:57.650
not passed it is the US.
Um, let me open this up more broadly.

00:48:57.650 --> 00:48:59.150
There are folks here.
We have a microphone.

00:48:59.150 --> 00:49:04.530
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm Michelle from San Francisco.
